WASHINGTON – United States (US) President Donald Trump opted Monday to hold fire on imposing steel and aluminum tariffs on the European Union, Canada and Mexico for 30 days. The move, which offers key allies a reprieve during ongoing negotiations, was announced by the White House. READ: Trump says US to impose steel, aluminum tariffs Washington also reached a deal with South Korea on steel imports, and "agreements in principle" with Argentina, Australia and Brazil, "the details of which will be finalised shortly," the White House added. The White House says the Trump administration is focusing on quotas that will restrain imports, prevent trans-shipment and protect national security. READ: SA seeks exclusion from Trump's steel and aluminium tariffs It is still not clear if South Africa’s request to be exempted will be granted by the US government. *Additional reporting eNCA AFP